04581nam a22007335i 9780231515528DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2008001172  a(OCoLC)979751598  a97802315155287 a10.7312/eldr144542doi  a(DE-B1597)458833  a(OCoLC)812924934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN49b.E43 2008 4aPN49 .E43 2008 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a801.31 aEldridge, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiterature, Life, and Modernity /cRichard Eldridge. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Subjectivity, Modernity, and the Uses of Literature -- t2. Romanticism, Cartesianism, Humeanism, Byronism Stoppard’s Arcadia -- t3. Romantic Subjectivity in Goethe and Wittgenstein -- t4. Attention, Expressive Power, and Interest in Life: Wordsworth’s “Tintern Abbey” -- t5. The Ends of Literary Narrative: Rilke’s “Archaic Torso of Apollo” -- t6. “New Centers of Reflection Are Continually Forming”: Benjamin, Sebald, and Modern Human Life in Time -- tAppendix: William Wordsworth: “Lines Composed a Few Miles Above Tintern Abbey” -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRichard Eldridge explores the ability of dense and formally interesting literature to respond to the complexities of modern life. Beyond simple entertainment, difficult modern works cultivate reflective depth and help their readers order and interpret their lives as subjects in relation to complex economies and technological systems. By imagining themselves in the role of the protagonist or the authorial persona, readers become immersed in structures of sustained attention, under which concrete possibilities of meaningful life, along with difficulties that block their realization, are tracked and clarified. Literary form, Eldridge argues, generates structures of care, reflection, and investment within readers, shapingif not stabilizingtheir interactions with everyday objects and events. Through the experience of literary forms of attention, readers may come to think and live more actively, more fully engaging with modern life, rather than passively suffering it. Eldridge considers the thought of Descartes, Kant, Adorno, Benjamin, Stanley Cavell, and Charles Taylor in his discussion of Goethe, Wordsworth, Rilke, Stoppard, and Sebald, advancing a philosophy of literature that addresses our desire to read and the meaning and satisfaction that literary attention brings to our fragmented modern lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEuropean literature - History and criticism. 0aEuropean literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and society. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/eldr1445440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231515528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231515528/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK